#import "template.typ": *

#let metadata = (
  title: "Climbing",
  unit: "Group A (3-Axis) | Phase 1 — Lesson 3 | E4, E8",
  author: "C.Moroney",
  version: "v1.0.0",
)

#let lesson = (
title: [Climbing]

,aim: [
Climb the aircraft at various rates and angles to a predetermined altitude, while maintaining balance.
]

,overview: [
The student builds on straight and level skills to enter, maintain, and level off from climbs at varying rates and angles. These include best rate (Vy) and best angle (Vx) climbs. This lesson continues the theme of attitude flying, and shows the student that _any_ performance is achieved with attitude and power combination. The PAT workcycle is used for climb entry; APT for level-off. The student begins managing climb performance, engine parameters, and lookout during extended climbs. E8 progression continues: the instructor handles the ground roll and lift-off; the student manages the initial climb.
]

,learning_outcomes: [
#text(size:12pt)[*Knowledge*]
- Recall the four forces and their interaction during a climb
- Explain that excess thrust enables the climb — not increased lift
- Describe the factors affecting climb performance (excess thrust available, weight, flap, density altitude, wind)
- Distinguish between Vy and Vx and their applications
- Explain why the nose should be lowered every 500 ft during extended climbs
- Describe engine temperature management considerations during climb

#text(size:12pt)[*Skills*]
- Initiate a climb from straight and level using the PAT workcycle
- Maintain Vy and Vx within +10/−0 kts, heading ±5°, in balance
- Lower nose every 500 ft and complete a clearing lookout
- Level off at a nominated altitude using the APT workcycle with correct anticipation
- Manage flap configuration and observe effect on climb performance
- Return the aircraft to the required climb profile following an unintended deviation or upset

#text(size:12pt)[*Non-Technical Skills*]
- [SA] Visual limitations in climb — high nose attitude restricts forward visibility
- [TEM] Engine overheat risk during prolonged climbs; terrain awareness and airspace ceiling
- [HF] Ear pressure awareness; report any discomfort immediately
]

,theory_knowledge: [
- Human Factors — ear problems, SA *(Pg 3, 10-11)*
- Aerodynamics — lift, thrust, pitching moment *(Pg 151-153)*
- Aeroplane Performance — take-off performance, pressure altitude *(Pg 145, 241)*
]

,ground_brief_topics: [
Total time: 40 minutes \
Equipment required: Aircraft model, access to electronic briefing, whiteboard \

*Non-Technical Skills* (5 minutes)
- [TEM] Engine overheat during sustained climb; terrain and airspace above
- [SA] Lookout in climb: forward visibility restricted; lower nose every 500 ft
- [HF] Ear pressure; Valsalva manoeuvre; report discomfort early

*Forces in a Climb* (10 minutes)
- Four forces in a steady climb; excess thrust provides climb — not increased lift
- Factors affecting climb performance: power, weight, flap, density altitude, turning, headwind vs tailwind

*Types of Climb/Terminology* (5 mins)
- Introduce terms "best rate" and "best angle"
- Vy: best rate of climb — maximum altitude per unit time
- Vx: best angle — maximum altitude per unit distance; steeper attitude, lower airspeed

*Attitude Flying in the Climb* (10 minutes)
- Entry: PAT — power smoothly, keep straight with rudder, climb attitude, trim
- Maintenance: LARI workcycle; lower nose every 500 ft for clearing lookout
- Level-off: APT — anticipate by 10% of climb rate; attitude to S&L, wait to accelerate, power smoothly reduce, trim

*Engine Management in Climb* (5 minutes)
- Monitor engine temps and pressures during extended climbs
- Effect of flap on climb performance: increased drag reduces rate and angle

*Instrument Use* (5 minutes)
- ASI: maintain Vy or Vx +10/-0 kts
- Altimeter: monitor climb progress
]

,ground_tasks:[
#text(size:12pt)[*Instructor*]
- Review weather, NOTAMs, and maintenance release (separately from student if needed due to time constraints)
- Complete the operations whiteboard and IMSAFE self-assessment with student
- Supervise pre-flight inspection with student; student identifies items checked
- Review training area airspace ceiling and EFATO brief structure

#text(size:12pt)[*Student*]
- Complete IMSAFE self-assessment and operations whiteboard
- Participate in pre-flight inspection and fuelling; briefing instructor on any items of note
- Set QNH; continue developing taxi and runup technique
]

,in_flight_tasks:[
#text(size:12pt)[*E8 Takeoff Progression — Lesson 3*]
Instructor conducts ground roll and lift-off. Student takes control immediately after lift-off, maintains climbout attitude and heading toward a reference point. Instructor monitors throughout.

#text(size:12pt)[*Demonstration*]
- Vy climb: full power, set attitude, trim, maintain Vy (±5 kts), hold heading ±5°
- Lower nose every 500 ft: demonstrate technique and lookout scan
- Level-off from Vy: APT workcycle, anticipate by ~50 ft
- Vx climb: steeper attitude, lower airspeed; demonstrate visual difference from Vy
- Effect of flap in climb: demonstrate degraded performance with flap extended

#text(size:12pt)[*Student Practice*]
- Vy climb: initiate from level flight using PAT; maintain Vy attitude and heading
- Lower nose every 500 ft: without prompting after first demonstration
- Level-off from Vy: apply APT; aim for ±100 ft of nominated altitude
- Vx climb: demonstrate understanding of difference from Vy
- Deviation correction: recognise ±10 kts airspeed or ±10° heading; correct with LARI
- Upset correction: return the aircraft to the correct Vx or Vy attitude after instructor induced upset
]

,common_errors:[
- *Airspeed chasing*: Set and hold the attitude; airspeed will follow.
- *Forgetting to lower nose every 500 ft*: Set a personal cue (altimeter reading or every 4th LARI cycle); build the habit from the start.
- *No rudder correction with full power*: Left-turning tendency — right rudder required from power application.
- *Levelling off late*: Anticipate; use 10% of ROC rule
- *No engine monitoring*: Every few LARI cycles, check engine temps and pressures
]

,post_flight:[
- *Student Self-Assessment* (5 min): Student describes performance (e.g. "I kept forgetting the nose-down lookout check").
- *Instructor Feedback* (5 min):
  - Evaluate against completion standards (P, S, C, or NC).
  - Highlight strengths and areas for improvement.
  - Discuss TEM/SA: "You asked about the airspace ceiling before the Vx climb — good TEM thinking."
- *Scenario Reflection* (5 min): "How would high density altitude affect Vy and Vx? What would you do differently on a hot day?"
- *Next Steps*: Assign homework.
]

,standards_for_progression:[
#text(size:12pt)[*Progressing — may advance to Lesson 4*]
- *Climb performance*: Airspeed +10/−5 kts, heading ±8°
- *Level-off*: Achieves nominated altitude ±200 ft; APT workcycle applied with minor prompting
- *Lookout*: Lowers nose every 500 ft with occasional reminders
- *Coordination*: Ball ±1/4 width with minor prompting
- *E8 progression*: Takes control after lift-off with light guidance; climbout attitude and heading generally maintained
- *Knowledge*: Describes Vy and Vx with minor prompting; understands excess thrust concept

#text(size:12pt)[*Solo Standard (S) — required before first solo*]
- *Climb performance*: Airspeed +5/-0 kts (S), heading ±5° (S)
- *Level-off*: Achieves nominated altitude ±150 ft (S) using PAT/APT workcycle
- *Lookout*: Lowers nose every 500 ft without prompting after first reminder
- *Coordination*: Ball ±1/4 width during climb and level-off
- *E8 progression*: Manages aircraft confidently from immediately after lift-off through climbout
- *Knowledge*: Explains Vy vs Vx and when to use each with minor prompting
- *Outcome*: Recorded in student records (P, S, C, or NC) with comments.
]

,safety:[
- *Weather*: Horizon clearly visible, ceiling >2000 ft, wind \<25 knots
- *Altitude*: Conduct manoeuvres above 1000 ft AGL; be aware of airspace ceiling
- *Emergency Procedures*: EFATO brief completed; forced landing area pre-selected
- *TEM*:
  - Monitor engine temperatures during sustained climbs; level off if approaching limits
  - Monitor student for ear discomfort; stop climbing if reported
  - Monitor for student anxiety or disorientation; pause, assess and continue or cut lesson short if needed
  - Maintain SA regarding controlled airspace
- *Aircraft Limits*: Do not exceed Vno; smooth throttle inputs
]

,homework:[
- Read Bob Tait's RAAus Study Guide:
  - Aerodynamics: Pages 151-153 (forces in climb, pitching moment, thrust vs lift)
  - Human Factors: Pages 1, 4 (IMSAFE, ear pressure)
  - Aeroplane Performance: Pages 145, 241 (climb performance, pressure altitude, instruments)
- Reflect on lesson: "How would high density altitude or turbulence affect climb performance? What adjustments would you make?"
]
)

#show: body => lesson_plan(metadata, lesson, body)